144	    /// Fetch and sync a set of repos to their remotes
145	    #[command(long_about = "Fetch and sync a set of repos to their remotes.\n\n\
146	        Repo set defaults to the dual-repo workspace pair (`.` and\n\
147	        `.claude`); override with `-R` / `--repo` for single-repo\n\
148	        projects or arbitrary multi-repo workspaces. Flag is repeatable\n\
149	        or comma-separated (e.g. `-R . -R .claude` or `-R .,.claude`).\n\n\
150	        Default is --check (verify only) — fatal if any repo needs\n\
151	        action. Re-run with --no-check to apply (rebase / fast-forward).\n\
152	        Per repo:\n  \
153	          - up-to-date        nothing to do\n  \
154	          - behind            fast-forward bookmark to remote\n  \
155	          - ahead             nothing to sync (local has unpushed work)\n  \
156	          - diverged          rebase local onto remote; fail on conflicts\n  \
157	          - no remote         bookmark has no @<remote> counterpart; skip\n\n\
158	        Scripts and automation should pass --check or --no-check\n\
159	        explicitly — defaults can shift, explicit flags lock in the\n\
160	        contract. Interactive use can rely on the default.\n\n\
161	        After the bookmark action, `@` is rebased onto the (possibly\n\
162	        advanced) bookmark if it isn't already a descendant, so trailing\n\
163	        working-copy writes (e.g. `.claude`'s `/exit` tail) don't end up\n\
164	        orphaned on a stale branch.\n\n\
165	        On any failure, every repo is reverted to its starting state via\n\
166	        `jj op restore`. Working-copy files are preserved across the\n\
167	        revert — the operation log rewinds but disk content stays.\n\n\
168	        Output shape:\n  \
169	          - all-up-to-date: one-line summary (`sync: N repos, all bookmarks up-to-date`)\n  \
170	          - action needed (--check):  per-repo fetch + state + fatal error\n  \
